219
00:17:22,097 --> 00:17:25,893
I don't know, Ma. I'm all knocked out.
I may just hang around the house.

220
00:17:26,018 --> 00:17:28,729
Why don't you go to
the Stardust Ballroom?

221
00:17:28,854 --> 00:17:30,064
What?

222
00:17:30,189 --> 00:17:35,694
I say "Why don't you go to the Stardust
Ballroom?" It's loaded with tomatoes.

223
00:17:35,819 --> 00:17:38,574
- It's loaded with what?
- Tomatoes.

224
00:17:38,698 --> 00:17:41,868
Who told you about
the Stardust Ballroom, Ma?

225
00:17:41,993 --> 00:17:46,122
- Tommy. He say it's very nice place.
- Oh, Thomas!

226
00:17:46,247 --> 00:17:50,126
Ma, it's just a big dance hall, that's all.
I been there a hundred times.

227
00:17:50,251 --> 00:17:52,879
Loaded with tomatoes!
Boy, you're funny, Ma.

228
00:17:53,005 --> 00:17:56,217
Marty, I don't want you
hanging around the house tonight.

229
00:17:56,342 --> 00:17:59,845
- I want you go shave and go dance.
- Ma, when are you gonna give up?

230
00:17:59,970 --> 00:18:03,808
- You got a bachelor on your hands.
- You gonna get married.

231
00:18:03,933 --> 00:18:08,271
Ma, sooner or later there comes a point
in a man's life when he's gotta face facts.

232
00:18:08,396 --> 00:18:11,900
One fact I gotta face is
whatever it is women like, I ain't got it.

233
00:18:12,025 --> 00:18:15,278
I chased after enough girls in my life.
I went to enough dances.

234
00:18:15,403 --> 00:18:17,905
I got hurt enough.
I don't wanna get hurt no more.

235
00:18:18,031 --> 00:18:21,452
I just called up a girl this afternoon.
I got a real brushoff, boy.

236
00:18:21,577 --> 00:18:24,495
I figured I was past the point
of bein' hurt, but that hurt.

237
00:18:24,622 --> 00:18:28,458
Some stupid woman who I didn't even
wanna call up. She gave me the brush.

238
00:18:28,583 --> 00:18:30,711
I don't wanna go to the Stardust Ballroom.

239
00:18:30,836 --> 00:18:34,965
All that ever happened to me there
was girls made me feel like I was a bug.

240
00:18:35,091 --> 00:18:38,594
I got feelings, you know.
I had enough pain. No, thanks, Ma.

241
00:18:38,719 --> 00:18:40,430
- Marty...
- No.

242
00:18:40,555 --> 00:18:42,640
I'm gonna stay home tonight.

243
00:18:42,765 --> 00:18:45,518
- You gonna die without a son.
- So I'll die without a son.

244
00:18:45,643 --> 00:18:49,272
- Marty, put on the blue suit, huh?
- Blue suit, grey suit.

245
00:18:49,397 --> 00:18:52,734
I'm just a fat, little man. A fat, ugly man.

246
00:18:52,859 --> 00:18:55,571
- You not ugly.
- I'm ugly! I'm ugly! I'm ugly!

247
00:18:55,696 --> 00:18:58,156
- Marty.
- Ma! Leave me alone!

248
00:19:00,117 --> 00:19:04,371
Ma, what do you want from me?
I'm miserable enough as it is.

249
00:19:04,496 --> 00:19:08,291
All right, I'll go to the Stardust Ballroom.
I'll put on a blue suit and go.

250
00:19:08,418 --> 00:19:13,380
You know what I'm gonna get for my
trouble? Heartache. A night of heartache!

251
00:19:28,062 --> 00:19:31,149
Loaded with tomatoes!

252
00:19:31,275 --> 00:19:33,401
That's rich.

253
00:20:01,848 --> 00:20:04,727
- Not a bad crowd tonight, you know?
- Yeah.

254
00:20:05,811 --> 00:20:09,481
There was a nice-lookin' one over there
with the black dress on.

255
00:20:09,607 --> 00:20:11,858
But she's dancin' now.

256
00:20:13,193 --> 00:20:16,739
Hey, there's a nice-lookin',
little short one for you down there.

257
00:20:16,864 --> 00:20:19,993
- Where?
- Down there. That little one down there.

258
00:20:23,413 --> 00:20:25,540
Oh, yeah.

259
00:20:25,665 --> 00:20:28,209
What do you say? Wanna ask 'em?

260
00:20:28,334 --> 00:20:31,421
I'll take the one
with the flowers on her dress.

261
00:20:33,214 --> 00:20:36,176
Well, I think this music's a little fast.

262
00:20:36,301 --> 00:20:38,345
Just a minute.

263
00:20:42,807 --> 00:20:46,354
Yeah, I think it's all right.
Are they still over there?

264
00:21:10,713 --> 00:21:12,965
What do you say? You wanna dance?

265
00:21:17,887 --> 00:21:21,348
Uh, excuse me. Would you care to dance?

266
00:21:21,474 --> 00:21:24,977
- I don't feel like dancin' just yet.
- Sure.

267
00:21:56,719 --> 00:21:59,138
Clara, have you decided about tomorrow?

268
00:21:59,264 --> 00:22:02,433
Millie, I always go to the movies
with Papa on Sunday.

269
00:22:02,559 --> 00:22:07,105
- I know, but you could have a lot of fun.
- I'm gonna get some cigarettes.

270
00:22:10,733 --> 00:22:15,613
Herb, I told you she wasn't especially
attractive, but she had a lot of charm.

271
00:22:15,738 --> 00:22:17,907
Look, Herb, she's a real nice kid.

272
00:22:18,034 --> 00:22:22,329
She's all right, Andy. It's just that I get
one Saturday night off every three weeks.

273
00:22:22,454 --> 00:22:24,498
I was expecting somethin' better.

274
00:22:24,624 --> 00:22:28,335
- D'you like him, Clara?
- Yes. He seems very nice.

275
00:22:29,212 --> 00:22:33,216
- Millie's been after me to fix her up.
- All right, I'm having a fair time.

276
00:22:33,341 --> 00:22:38,137
I get one Saturday night off in three weeks
and I wanted to wind up with something.

277
00:22:38,262 --> 00:22:40,307
- OK. So I'm sorry.
- Forget it.

278
00:23:09,504 --> 00:23:12,508
- Herbie, have you ever been here before?
- Hey!

279
00:23:12,633 --> 00:23:14,468
Herbie!

280
00:23:14,593 --> 00:23:18,555
- What are you doing here?
- I came up to dance. What do you think?

281
00:23:18,680 --> 00:23:22,142
- You here with somebody?
- I'm just here with another girl.

282
00:23:22,267 --> 00:23:26,647
- Where you goin' now?
- For some cigarettes. Left 'em in my coat.

283
00:23:26,772 --> 00:23:29,650
- I'll see you around.
- Yeah, I'll see ya.

284
00:23:34,531 --> 00:23:36,741
Oh, that's a... girl I used to know.

285
00:23:49,379 --> 00:23:53,050
- Boy, it's sure packed in here.
- Some of these kids are awfully young.

286
00:23:53,175 --> 00:23:55,468
You might run into one of your students.

287
00:23:55,593 --> 00:23:58,055
I wouldn't think so.
I teach out in Brooklyn.

288
00:23:58,180 --> 00:24:02,143
- Oh, you been here before, Clara?
- Yes. Twice.

289
00:24:02,268 --> 00:24:06,689
You wanna try and get a table and a drink,
or you just wanna start dancing?

290
00:24:06,814 --> 00:24:11,027
Well, Herb... Herb! What do you say?
We grab a table before we dance?

291
00:24:11,152 --> 00:24:15,114
Listen, you people go grab a table.
I'll be back in a minute.

292
00:24:15,239 --> 00:24:17,283
I'll be right back.

293
00:24:18,326 --> 00:24:21,830
What do you say, Clara, huh?
Come on, we'll grab a table.

294
00:24:52,236 --> 00:24:56,700
- You here stag or with a girl?
- You say somethin'?

295
00:24:56,825 --> 00:24:59,912
Yeah. I was askin' you
if you was here stag or with a girl.

296
00:25:00,037 --> 00:25:04,668
- Oh, I'm stag.
- I got stuck on a blind date with a dog.

297
00:25:04,792 --> 00:25:09,130
I just met an old girl I used to know,
so I need to get rid of the girl I'm with.

298
00:25:09,255 --> 00:25:12,091
Somebody to take her home,
you know what I mean?

299
00:25:12,216 --> 00:25:16,513
- I'd pay you $5 if you take her home.
- What?

300
00:25:16,638 --> 00:25:20,516
I'll introduce you as an old army buddy
of mine and then I'll cut out,

301
00:25:20,641 --> 00:25:25,856
because I got this other girl waiting for
me by the hatcheck, and I'll pay you $5.

302
00:25:25,981 --> 00:25:28,692
- Are you kiddin'?
- No, I'm not kiddin'.

303
00:25:30,027 --> 00:25:32,905
You just can't walk off on a girl like that!

304
00:26:57,744 --> 00:27:00,788
As long as she's goin' home alone,
give me the $5 back.

305
00:27:00,914 --> 00:27:03,667
Look, Mac, you paid me the $5.
The $5 is mine.

306
00:27:58,933 --> 00:28:01,977
Excuse me, miss,
but would you care to dance?

307
00:28:05,690 --> 00:28:07,525
Miss?

308
00:28:48,359 --> 00:28:52,531
- You come up here often?
- I was up here twice before.

309
00:28:52,656 --> 00:28:56,035
Once I came up with a friend of mine
and... once alone.

310
00:28:57,494 --> 00:28:59,538
The last time...

311
00:29:00,706 --> 00:29:03,543
You see that girl sitting over there
in the grey dress?

312
00:29:03,668 --> 00:29:04,794
Yeah.

313
00:29:04,919 --> 00:29:08,631
Well, the last time I was here,
that's where I sat.

314
00:29:10,049 --> 00:29:13,887
I sat there for an hour and a half
without moving a muscle.

315
00:29:14,930 --> 00:29:20,394
Now and then some fellow would kind of
come up to me and then change his mind.

316
00:29:22,562 --> 00:29:27,193
I'll never forget just sitting there for an
hour and a half with my hands in my lap.

317
00:29:27,318 --> 00:29:30,154
Then I began to cry.
I had to get up and go home.

318
00:29:31,363 --> 00:29:33,949
I've begun to cry a lot lately.

319
00:29:34,074 --> 00:29:37,286
I cry a lot, too. I'm a big crier.

320
00:29:37,411 --> 00:29:41,957
This is something recent with me, this
bursting into tears at the slightest thing.

321
00:29:42,082 --> 00:29:44,752
I cry all the time, any little thing.

322
00:29:44,877 --> 00:29:49,758
My brothers, my brothers-in-law always
tell me what a good-hearted guy I am.

323
00:29:49,883 --> 00:29:51,926
You're not good-hearted by accident.

324
00:29:52,051 --> 00:29:56,348
You get kicked around long enough,
you get to be a real professor of pain.

325
00:29:56,473 --> 00:29:58,476
I know exactly how you feel.

326
00:29:58,601 --> 00:30:03,688
I also want you to know I'm having a good
time with you and really enjoyin' myself.

327
00:30:03,815 --> 00:30:07,192
So, you see, you're not such a dog
as you think you are.

328
00:30:12,156 --> 00:30:15,201
I'm having a very good time, too.

329
00:30:15,326 --> 00:30:19,705
So there you are. So I guess
I'm not such a dog as I think I am.

330
00:30:19,830 --> 00:30:22,167
No, you're a very nice guy.

331
00:30:22,292 --> 00:30:25,921
I don't know why some girl
hasn't grabbed you off long ago.

332
00:30:26,046 --> 00:30:29,758
Well, I don't know either.
I think I'm a very nice guy.

333
00:30:29,883 --> 00:30:34,096
I also think I'm a pretty smart guy
in my own way. Excuse me.

334
00:30:34,221 --> 00:30:39,184
I figure two people get married and
they're gonna live together 40, 50 years,

335
00:30:39,311 --> 00:30:43,398
so it's gotta be more than
whether they're just good-lookin' or not.

336
00:30:43,523 --> 00:30:45,608
You think you're not so good-lookin'.

337
00:30:45,733 --> 00:30:49,654
Well, my father was a real ugly man,
but my mother adored him.

338
00:30:49,779 --> 00:30:53,783
She told me how she'd get so miserable
sometimes, like everybody, you know?

339
00:30:53,908 --> 00:30:57,996
And she says my father
always tried to understand.

340
00:30:58,121 --> 00:31:02,960
I used to see them sometimes when
I was a kid sittin' in the livin' room talkin',

341
00:31:03,085 --> 00:31:07,089
and I used to adore my old man,
because he was always so kind.

342
00:31:07,214 --> 00:31:11,719
That's one of the most beautiful things I
have in my life - the way my parents were.

343
00:31:11,844 --> 00:31:14,263
And my father was a real ugly man.

344
00:31:14,388 --> 00:31:17,308
So it doesn't matter
if you look like a gorilla.

345
00:31:17,433 --> 00:31:20,895
See, dogs like us,
we ain't such dogs as we think we are.

346
00:31:27,026 --> 00:31:29,696
I'm 29 years old.

347
00:31:30,530 --> 00:31:33,324
How old are you?

348
00:31:33,450 --> 00:31:35,910
I'm 34.

349
00:31:55,556 --> 00:31:59,560
- Oh, hello, Aunt Theresa. Come on in.
- Is Caterina here?

350
00:31:59,685 --> 00:32:02,564
We didn't say anything.
We thought we'd leave it to you.

351
00:32:02,689 --> 00:32:06,985
We thought you'd put it like how you were
lonely and why doesn't she live with you.

352
00:32:07,111 --> 00:32:12,907
That way it looks like she's doing you
a favour, instead of we're throwin' her out.

353
00:32:13,034 --> 00:32:17,996
- You want Tommy and me to stay?
- No. It's better idea if you and Tommy go,

354
00:32:18,121 --> 00:32:21,959
otherwise she's gonna start to fight
with you and everybody be yelling.

355
00:32:22,084 --> 00:32:24,128
- Hello, Aunt Theresa.
- Hello, Thomas.

356
00:32:24,253 --> 00:32:26,672
Who's there? Who's there?

357
00:32:26,798 --> 00:32:30,176
- It's me, Caterina! How you feel?
- Hey, what are you doin' here?

358
00:32:30,301 --> 00:32:32,262
I come to see you. How you feel?

359
00:32:32,387 --> 00:32:35,682
I got a pain on my left side
and my leg throbs like a drum.

360
00:32:35,807 --> 00:32:39,977
- I been getting pain in my shoulder.
- Hah! I got a pain in my shoulder, too.

361
00:32:40,104 --> 00:32:45,150
I got a pain in my hip and
my right arm aches so much I can't sleep.

362
00:32:45,275 --> 00:32:47,612
Ah, it's a curse to be old.

363
00:32:47,737 --> 00:32:51,699
We got a postcard from
my son Nicky and his bride.

364
00:32:51,824 --> 00:32:55,202
They are in Florida in a big hotel
on their honeymoon.

365
00:32:55,786 --> 00:32:59,957
I got a letter from
my husband's cousin in Abruzzi.

366
00:33:00,083 --> 00:33:02,501
- His mother die.
- Oh.

367
00:33:02,627 --> 00:33:06,589
You remember Emilio DiGiorgio,
who own a tavern in Abruzzi?

368
00:33:07,090 --> 00:33:09,300
- He die.
- Oh.

369
00:33:09,425 --> 00:33:13,304
- You know who else die?
- Who?

370
00:33:13,430 --> 00:33:20,228
You know the old man who live upstairs
in this house? Irishman, always drunk.

371
00:33:20,353 --> 00:33:25,693
He get pleurisy. He stay two weeks
in a hospital. Yesterday he die.

372
00:33:26,569 --> 00:33:32,575
I like to visit you, Caterina, because
you always got such cheerful news.

373
00:33:32,700 --> 00:33:36,329
Hey, kids. Why don't you two kids
go to the movies?

374
00:33:36,454 --> 00:33:38,748
Your mother and me, we be baby-sitter.

375
00:33:38,873 --> 00:33:42,627
- Let's go down to the Kaplans'.
- Sure, sure.

376
00:33:42,752 --> 00:33:46,882
Ma, we'll be down at the Kaplans'
if you want us for anything. OK?

377
00:33:53,764 --> 00:33:56,975
I wake up this morning.
I hear the baby cry, so I wake up.

378
00:33:57,100 --> 00:34:01,230
I come in their room, and that girl,
she's shakin' her hand at the baby.

379
00:34:01,355 --> 00:34:06,361
I said "You brute! Don't you strike
that baby! That's my son's baby!"

380
00:34:06,486 --> 00:34:08,947
- It's her baby, too.
- It's my son Thomas's baby.

381
00:34:09,072 --> 00:34:10,698
But it's not your baby.

382
00:34:10,823 --> 00:34:12,867
I tell you she throw a bottle of milk at me?

383
00:34:12,992 --> 00:34:14,912
I know. I know.

384
00:34:15,036 --> 00:34:17,997
She's a witch, that one, I tell you.

385
00:34:18,122 --> 00:34:20,375
- I tell you what she do yesterday?
- What?

386
00:34:20,500 --> 00:34:22,836
- She give me the evil eye.
- Uffa Caterina.

387
00:34:22,961 --> 00:34:28,425
I keep one eye open when I sleep,
because she's gonna stab me in my bed.

388
00:34:28,550 --> 00:34:32,804
Caterina, I want you to come
and live with me in my house.

389
00:34:33,181 --> 00:34:34,598
Hm?

390
00:34:34,723 --> 00:34:38,395
Your son Thomas and his wife,
they come to my house today.

391
00:34:38,853 --> 00:34:41,689
They say things
are no good in this house.

392
00:34:41,816 --> 00:34:44,567
Caterina, your son is married.

393
00:34:44,692 --> 00:34:48,321
Leave him in peace.
He wants to be alone with his wife.

394
00:34:48,446 --> 00:34:51,115
They don't want no old woman
sittin' in the balcony.

395
00:34:51,240 --> 00:34:55,120
My son Thomas
come to see you this afternoon,

396
00:34:55,246 --> 00:34:59,667
and he say to you he's gonna
throw his mother from this house?

397
00:34:59,999 --> 00:35:04,296
Ooh, Caterina,
don't make an opera out of this.

398
00:35:04,421 --> 00:35:07,675
The three of you and a little baby
in three skinny little rooms.

399
00:35:07,967 --> 00:35:12,721
You know this is no good - old woman
living with a husband and wife.

400
00:35:12,846 --> 00:35:15,600
Two women in the same kitchen,
the house burns up.

401
00:35:15,725 --> 00:35:19,395
So I'm an old garbage bag
put in the street, huh?

402
00:35:19,520 --> 00:35:22,398
Caterina, don't make a tragedy.

403
00:35:23,358 --> 00:35:27,737
Come and live in my house where
you know you be more happier yourself.

404
00:35:30,157 --> 00:35:32,451
It pains they should do this.

405
00:35:35,204 --> 00:35:37,915
I know it pains.

406
00:35:39,375 --> 00:35:41,835
These are the worst years, I tell you.

407
00:35:42,128 --> 00:35:45,423
Caterina, you are very dear to me.

408
00:35:46,341 --> 00:35:49,386
We cried lots of times together.

409
00:35:49,511 --> 00:35:54,641
When my poor husband, he die,
I would be crazy if not for you.

410
00:35:54,766 --> 00:36:00,021
I ask you to come to my house,
because I know I can make you happy.

411
00:36:00,146 --> 00:36:02,399
Please come to my house, Caterina.

412
00:36:03,316 --> 00:36:05,987
These are the worst years, I tell you.

413
00:36:06,112 --> 00:36:08,280
It's gonna happen to you.

414
00:36:08,405 --> 00:36:10,449
I'm afraid to look in a mirror.

415
00:36:10,574 --> 00:36:14,996
I'm afraid I'm gonna see an old lady with
white hair, like the old ladies in the park -

416
00:36:15,121 --> 00:36:19,375
little bundles in black shawl,
waiting for the coffin.

417
00:36:19,500 --> 00:36:23,337
I'm 56 years old,
and what I got to do with myself?

418
00:36:23,462 --> 00:36:27,550
I got strength in my hands.
I wanna clean, I wanna cook.

419
00:36:27,676 --> 00:36:30,263
I wanna make dinner for my children.

420
00:36:30,387 --> 00:36:35,017
Am I an old dog to lay near the fire
till my eyes close?

421
00:36:35,142 --> 00:36:39,605
These are terrible years, Theresa.
Terrible years.

422
00:36:42,441 --> 00:36:44,444
Caterina, listen...

423
00:36:44,570 --> 00:36:48,155
It's gonna happen to you.
It's gonna happen to you!

424
00:36:49,282 --> 00:36:52,701
What are you gonna do
if Marty gets married, huh?

425
00:36:52,826 --> 00:36:54,870
What are you gonna cook?

426
00:36:54,995 --> 00:36:59,876
Where's all the children playin'
in all the rooms? Where's the noise?

427
00:37:00,001 --> 00:37:03,713
It's a curse to be a widow. A curse!

428
00:37:04,840 --> 00:37:07,760
What are you gonna do
if Marty gets married?

429
00:37:07,884 --> 00:37:10,137
What are you gonna do?

430
00:37:13,390 --> 00:37:16,060
I'm gonna put my things in a bag,

431
00:37:17,603 --> 00:37:19,897
and I come to you tomorrow.

432
00:37:31,076 --> 00:37:33,453
Don't worry. We'll come right back.

433
00:37:33,578 --> 00:37:35,371
You teach chemistry? What school?

434
00:37:35,498 --> 00:37:38,208
- Benjamin Franklin High School.
- In Brooklyn?

435
00:37:38,332 --> 00:37:41,586
I went to Theodore Roosevelt
on Fordham Road. It's near my house.

436
00:37:41,711 --> 00:37:44,589
I have a cousin who's a teacher.
He teaches Latin.

437
00:37:44,715 --> 00:37:47,425
He was studying to be a priest,
but he gave it up.

438
00:37:47,552 --> 00:37:50,638
I was pretty good in high school.
I sound like a jerk now.

439
00:37:50,763 --> 00:37:52,932
I got an 82 average. That ain't bad.

440
00:37:53,057 --> 00:37:57,102
I was accepted at City College, but
my old man died, so I had to go to work.

441
00:37:57,228 --> 00:37:58,646
Want some cigarettes?

442
00:37:58,771 --> 00:38:01,482
German was my best class.
That was my best language.

443
00:38:01,607 --> 00:38:05,112
Der, die, das. Des, der, des.
There you are, I still remember.

444
00:38:06,571 --> 00:38:09,283
You know what I was
good at in high school? Math.

445
00:38:09,409 --> 00:38:12,869
You know how long ago
I graduated high school? June 1937.

446
00:38:12,994 --> 00:38:17,999
Holy cow! June 1937!
What is that? 15... 17 years ago!

447
00:38:18,125 --> 00:38:22,212
Holy cow! Seven... Let's see, is that right?
Yeah, 17. That's right.

448
00:38:22,337 --> 00:38:27,760
Where'd it all go? I'm gettin' old. I'm
gonna be 35 years old November 8th. 35!

449
00:38:27,885 --> 00:38:30,014
Wow! Time goes on, boy!

450
00:38:30,138 --> 00:38:32,431
Yeah. 19... June 1937.

451
00:38:32,556 --> 00:38:36,644
My old man died December 1937.
Two o'clock in the mornin', he died.

452
00:38:36,769 --> 00:38:40,773
Bell rings. I knew somethin' was wrong
because my room is on the ground floor.

453
00:38:40,899 --> 00:38:44,402
I had to get outta bed to answer the door,
and there was Mr Stern.

454
00:38:44,527 --> 00:38:48,325
He had a house down about a block away
from us. He moved out, though.

455
00:38:48,449 --> 00:38:52,286
My old man played cards with him and
some other guys. He was a Jewish fella.

456
00:38:52,411 --> 00:38:57,374
So he said "Is your mother home?"
So I knew there was somethin' wrong.

457
00:38:57,499 --> 00:39:00,794
I was only 18, exactly 18 years old
just a month before.

458
00:39:00,920 --> 00:39:04,591
So I said "Is something wrong, Mr Stern?"
I was in my pyjamas.

459
00:39:04,716 --> 00:39:07,468
So he said "Marty, your father died."

460
00:39:07,593 --> 00:39:11,013
My father died right in the middle
of playin' cards, at the table.

461
00:39:11,138 --> 00:39:13,850
He had a heart attack.
He had low blood pressure.

462
00:39:13,975 --> 00:39:16,602
He used to faint a lot, you know.

463
00:39:16,729 --> 00:39:18,771
Boy... Boy, am I talkin'!

464
00:39:18,898 --> 00:39:21,859
Excuse me.
I never talked so much in all my life.

465
00:39:21,984 --> 00:39:24,362
Usually everybody tells me their troubles.

466
00:39:24,487 --> 00:39:27,614
Well, I'm gonna shut up now
and let you get a word in.

467
00:39:27,739 --> 00:39:30,326
Yeah, 17 years ago.

468
00:39:30,451 --> 00:39:33,328
What I been doin' with myself
all that time?

469
00:39:33,455 --> 00:39:36,582
Well, there I go again!
I must be drivin' you crazy.

470
00:39:36,707 --> 00:39:39,877
Most of the time I'm with a girl
I... I can't find a word to say.

471
00:39:40,002 --> 00:39:43,799
I'm gonna shut up and let you get a word
in, because usually I'm not like this.

472
00:39:43,924 --> 00:39:45,759
Usually I...

473
00:39:45,884 --> 00:39:48,845
There I go again! I can't stop talkin'.

474
00:39:48,970 --> 00:39:52,098
I'm on a jag, for Pete's sakes!
You'd think I was loaded.

475
00:39:52,224 --> 00:39:55,393
Well, anyway, like... like I started to say...

476
00:39:55,519 --> 00:39:57,563
Ahi!

477
00:39:59,648 --> 00:40:02,944
I can't stop my mouth. Isn't this stupid?

478
00:40:04,529 --> 00:40:06,697
You got a real nice face, you know.

479
00:40:07,031 --> 00:40:09,075
Really, a nice face.

480
00:40:10,034 --> 00:40:11,786
Thank you.

481
00:41:03,632 --> 00:41:07,136
- Hey, Mac. Anything good inside?
- A bunch of dogs.

482
00:41:11,348 --> 00:41:13,393
Hey, Marty.

483
00:41:14,310 --> 00:41:16,353
Marty, you in here?

484
00:41:43,925 --> 00:41:45,551
So I'm in a kneeling position,

485
00:41:45,676 --> 00:41:50,014
and if you ever tried shootin' a BAR in a
kneeling position, you know what I mean.

486
00:41:50,139 --> 00:41:53,977
I can't hold a steady position.
I'm waverin' back and forth.

487
00:41:55,437 --> 00:41:58,356
So the guy next to me,
he's shootin' from a prone position,

488
00:41:58,482 --> 00:42:00,858
and he's cross-eyed, like I told you.

489
00:42:04,153 --> 00:42:06,782
So just then...

490
00:42:06,907 --> 00:42:10,620
So just then I hear five shots go off
from the guy next to me.

491
00:42:12,538 --> 00:42:17,543
My target goes down. A minute later
the flag comes up. I got five bull's-eyes!

492
00:42:21,131 --> 00:42:26,093
That's how I got the reputation of being
the best shot in the whole battalion!

493
00:42:40,650 --> 00:42:44,113
So when I got out of the army,
Clara, I was lost.

494
00:42:44,238 --> 00:42:47,032
I didn't know what I wanted to do.

495
00:42:47,158 --> 00:42:49,327
I was 25 years old.

496
00:42:49,452 --> 00:42:53,081
What was I gonna do?
Go back to my old job, 40 cents an hour?

497
00:42:54,207 --> 00:42:57,835
I thought maybe I'd go to college
under the GI Bill of Rights.

498
00:42:59,170 --> 00:43:05,051
But my brother Freddie wanted to get
married and I had three unmarried sisters.

499
00:43:05,176 --> 00:43:08,304
In an Italian house, that's a terrible thing.

500
00:43:08,430 --> 00:43:11,308
So I just went to pieces.

501
00:43:13,227 --> 00:43:17,481
I used to walk the streets
till three, four o'clock in the mornin'.

502
00:43:19,566 --> 00:43:23,905
My poor mother...
used to be so worried about me.

503
00:43:29,410 --> 00:43:32,247
God forgive me what
I'm gonna say now, but...

504
00:43:34,123 --> 00:43:36,918
I used to think of doin' away with myself.

505
00:43:38,503 --> 00:43:43,675
I used to stand on the subway and,
God forgive me what I'm gonna say, I...

506
00:43:44,843 --> 00:43:47,846
I used to feel the tracks
suckin' me down under the wheels.

507
00:43:47,971 --> 00:43:49,597
Yes, I know.

508
00:43:49,724 --> 00:43:53,853
I'm Catholic, you know. Even
to think about suicide is a terrible sin.

509
00:43:54,311 --> 00:43:56,564
Yes, I know.

510
00:43:58,690 --> 00:44:03,071
So then Mr Otari, he offered me this job
in his butcher shop and...

511
00:44:03,196 --> 00:44:05,948
Everybody pleaded with me to take it.

512
00:44:06,074 --> 00:44:08,117
So that's what happened.

513
00:44:09,035 --> 00:44:11,079
I didn't wanna be a butcher.

514
00:44:12,373 --> 00:44:15,209
There's nothing wrong
with being a butcher.

515
00:44:16,876 --> 00:44:19,797
Well, it's not an elegant profession.

516
00:44:19,922 --> 00:44:23,884
It's in the lower social scale.
People look down on butchers.

517
00:44:24,009 --> 00:44:26,053
I don't.

518
00:44:28,514 --> 00:44:33,061
Well, the point is Mr Otari
wants to sell his shop now because...

519
00:44:33,186 --> 00:44:38,107
It's a nice little shop. I handle his books

520
00:44:38,232 --> 00:44:40,694
which is not unreasonable.

521
00:44:41,987 --> 00:44:46,074
Takes home net
maybe $100, $150 a week.

522
00:44:46,199 --> 00:44:49,494
Point is, of course, you gotta
worry about the supermarkets.

523
00:44:49,619 --> 00:44:55,000
There's two in the neighbourhood and an
A&P comin' in, at least that's the rumour.

524
00:44:55,126 --> 00:45:00,131
Marty, it's my feeling that
you really want to buy this shop.

525
00:45:01,465 --> 00:45:03,592
Well, that's true. I do.

526
00:45:03,717 --> 00:45:07,973
But it means I gotta take a loan
out in a bank of $8,000.

527
00:45:08,098 --> 00:45:10,142
That's a big note to carry.

528
00:45:11,977 --> 00:45:18,608
Marty, I've known you for three hours,
but I know you're a good butcher.

529
00:45:19,693 --> 00:45:23,863
You're an intelligent,
decent, sensitive man,

530
00:45:23,989 --> 00:45:28,494
and... well, I have a feeling about you.

531
00:45:28,619 --> 00:45:34,458
Like, well, like sometimes one of my kids
comes to see me about something,

532
00:45:34,583 --> 00:45:37,753
and some of these kids, Marty,
in my classes, they...

533
00:45:37,878 --> 00:45:42,008
they have so much warmth
and so much capacity.

534
00:45:44,427 --> 00:45:48,724
Well, that's the feeling I have about you.

535
00:45:50,350 --> 00:45:53,102
If you were one of my students,
I'd say to you

536
00:45:53,227 --> 00:45:57,858
"Go ahead and buy the butcher shop.
You're a good butcher."

537
00:46:05,366 --> 00:46:08,995
Well, there's lots of things
I could do with this shop.

538
00:46:09,121 --> 00:46:11,622
I could organise my own supermarket.

539
00:46:11,747 --> 00:46:14,959
Get a bunch of neighbourhood
merchants together.

540
00:46:15,085 --> 00:46:17,712
That's what a lot of them are doin'.

541
00:46:20,132 --> 00:46:21,966
What do you think?

542
00:46:22,091 --> 00:46:25,554
I think anything you wanna do
you'll do well.

543
00:46:27,514 --> 00:46:29,849
I'm Catholic. Are you Catholic?

544
00:46:33,103 --> 00:46:35,147
Yes, I am.

545
00:46:39,151 --> 00:46:44,865
Look, I only got about $3 on me now, but
I only live about eight blocks from here.

546
00:46:44,990 --> 00:46:49,495
Why don't we go back to my house, I'll get
some dough and we can go somewhere?

547
00:46:49,620 --> 00:46:51,330
I... I really should get home.

548
00:46:51,455 --> 00:46:54,376
It's only a quarter of 12.
The clock's right up there.

549
00:46:55,044 --> 00:46:58,171
I... I really should get home.
I told my father...

550
00:47:00,632 --> 00:47:03,552
Well, I... I suppose a little while longer...

551
00:47:04,886 --> 00:47:09,475
Do you suppose there's someplace
around here I could put on some makeup?

552
00:47:09,600 --> 00:47:13,104
Oh. Hey, Mac!
You got a ladies' room around here?

553
00:47:13,229 --> 00:47:15,273
- In the back.
- In the back.

554
00:48:22,676 --> 00:48:25,763
- She told me, at the risk of her life.
- She always had thin hips.

555
00:48:25,889 --> 00:48:30,560
She told me the doctor told her, if she had
more babies, it'd be at the risk of her life.

556
00:48:30,685 --> 00:48:33,313
When she told me that,
she already had six!

557
00:48:33,438 --> 00:48:37,651
Every time I saw her, she was either
goin' to the hospital or comin' from it.

558
00:48:37,776 --> 00:48:41,446
- She was hatchin' 'em out like eggs.
- Her husband's a skinny fella.

559
00:48:41,571 --> 00:48:46,076
Well, I bumped into her on the street
and she was as big as a barrel.

560
00:48:46,201 --> 00:48:48,454
- I said to her "Mary..."
- Lou, seen Marty?

561
00:48:48,579 --> 00:48:51,915
- No, I ain't seen him all night.
- Where's everybody?

562
00:48:52,040 --> 00:48:54,795
"Didn't you say if you
had another it'd kill you?"

563
00:48:54,919 --> 00:48:56,921
And her husband's a little bit of a man.

564
00:48:57,046 --> 00:49:01,426
Well, last week on Tuesday she gave birth
to her baby in St Elizabeth's Hospital.

565
00:49:01,551 --> 00:49:06,431
- A fine, healthy boy. Nine pounds.
- That's fine. So the doctor was wrong.

566
00:49:06,556 --> 00:49:09,184
Oh, no. She died
right there in the hospital.

567
00:49:09,309 --> 00:49:12,395
Oh, that's a sad story.

568
00:49:13,063 --> 00:49:16,692
- And her husband's that little fella?
- That's the one.

569
00:49:16,817 --> 00:49:19,069
That's a sad story.

570
00:49:42,469 --> 00:49:46,848
...moving out to Port Chester.
It's silly to think of commuting.

571
00:49:46,973 --> 00:49:52,021
I'd have to take the subway down to
125th, then take the bus to the railroad,

572
00:49:52,146 --> 00:49:55,607
and then take the New York, New Haven
and Hartford out to Port Chester.

573
00:49:55,732 --> 00:49:59,486
Then I think I have a 20-minute bus ride
out of Port Chester.

574
00:50:00,404 --> 00:50:04,409
Somebody suggested that I buy a car,
but I'm terrified of cars.

575
00:50:05,243 --> 00:50:07,620
I'm always afraid I'll kill someone.

576
00:50:09,998 --> 00:50:13,459
Of course, it is a fine opportunity for me.

577
00:50:13,584 --> 00:50:17,547
I could never hope to be the head of a
department in the New York City system,

578
00:50:17,672 --> 00:50:20,508
especially not in the science courses.

579
00:50:22,052 --> 00:50:25,389
Of course, I'm not sure
I want to be a department head.

580
00:50:25,514 --> 00:50:28,976
It's mostly executive
and administrative work.

581
00:50:29,101 --> 00:50:31,145
On the other hand...

582
00:50:32,397 --> 00:50:36,401
Well, anyway I told you about my father

583
00:50:36,526 --> 00:50:39,028
and, well, he depends on me a great deal.

584
00:50:39,403 --> 00:50:43,575
Well, let me tell ya, Clara.
I think you're kiddin' yourself.

585
00:50:43,700 --> 00:50:46,411
I mean, I used to think about
leavin' home, you know.

586
00:50:46,536 --> 00:50:49,289
And that's what I used to say:
"My mother needs me."

587
00:50:49,414 --> 00:50:53,460
But when you really come down to it,
that ain't it at all.

588
00:50:53,585 --> 00:50:58,173
We're just afraid to go out on our own. It's
a big step when you go out on your own.

589
00:50:58,298 --> 00:51:02,344
And I think you're kiddin' yourself
when you say your father needs you.

590
00:51:02,469 --> 00:51:05,514
Actually, you need your father.
You know what I mean?

591
00:51:05,640 --> 00:51:07,475
Well, you know what I mean.

592
00:51:07,808 --> 00:51:11,437
You're livin' at home now and
you've got your father and mother there.

593
00:51:11,562 --> 00:51:14,649
You could go on like that,
be a little girl all your life.

594
00:51:14,774 --> 00:51:17,110
I'm afraid of being lonely.

595
00:51:17,235 --> 00:51:20,989
You won't be so lonely.
You'll make friends right away.

596
00:51:21,114 --> 00:51:25,953
Well, actually, I don't make friends easily.

597
00:51:26,078 --> 00:51:29,165
What are you talkin' about?
You're a real likeable person.

598
00:51:29,289 --> 00:51:32,210
You'll make friends
in Port Chester one-two-three.

599
00:51:32,335 --> 00:51:35,505
You'll have people visitin' you
all the time. I'll visit you.

600
00:51:35,630 --> 00:51:40,551
I'll get my brother Freddie's car
or you can call me up when you feel blue.

601
00:51:40,676 --> 00:51:42,970
Or I'll call you up and...

602
00:51:43,095 --> 00:51:46,390
It'll be real nice. Don't be so afraid.

603
00:51:54,357 --> 00:51:56,235
Hey, Marty!

604
00:51:56,401 --> 00:51:59,655
Hey, Marty! Hey, over here!

605
00:52:00,614 --> 00:52:03,742
- Hello, Ralph.
- Hey, Marty. Come over here a minute.

606
00:52:05,328 --> 00:52:07,538
- Excuse me a minute.
- Sure.

607
00:52:10,165 --> 00:52:12,668
- You'll like this guy. He's nice.
- Who? Marty?

608
00:52:12,793 --> 00:52:16,172
- Yeah.
- Oh, this guy's a nice guy, this guy.

609
00:52:16,297 --> 00:52:18,799
- Hi, Ralph. Hello, Leo.
- Hiya, Marty.

610
00:52:18,924 --> 00:52:21,052
Hey, Marty, come here a minute.

611
00:52:21,177 --> 00:52:24,597
Hey, Marty, we got an odd squirrel.
You interested?

612
00:52:24,722 --> 00:52:26,809
What do you mean, Ralph?

613
00:52:26,934 --> 00:52:30,436
Hey, Louise, meet Marty Piletti.
Marty, that's Louise Kelly.

614
00:52:30,563 --> 00:52:34,441
- Hiya.
- We just gonna sit around here all night?

615
00:52:34,566 --> 00:52:38,696
Listen, Marty,
these three squirrels are nurses.

616
00:52:38,820 --> 00:52:41,448
Money in the bank, man.

617
00:52:41,573 --> 00:52:45,327
All goin' over to Leo's house later
because there's nobody there.

618
00:52:45,452 --> 00:52:47,747
These are the girls I told you about.

619
00:52:48,665 --> 00:52:52,460
Wanna get in the car?
She's a pretty nice-lookin' doll.

620
00:52:52,585 --> 00:52:57,799
- I'm with a girl, Ralph.
- Get rid of her. This is money in the bank.

621
00:52:57,924 --> 00:53:02,470
I can't do that, because somebody
already brushed her off once tonight.

622
00:53:02,595 --> 00:53:05,057
This is a good deal here, Marty.

623
00:53:14,900 --> 00:53:17,695
I can't do it, Ralph. Thanks anyway, huh?

624
00:53:19,196 --> 00:53:22,116
- Nice seein' you all.
- Come on, let's get outta here.

625
00:53:22,241 --> 00:53:25,453
- Yeah. We might as well get goin'.
- I'll see ya, Leo.

626
00:53:25,578 --> 00:53:27,915
- So long, Ralph.
- So long, Marty.

627
00:54:07,330 --> 00:54:09,583
Wait a minute. I'll find the light.

628
00:54:14,922 --> 00:54:17,049
I guess my mother ain't home yet.

629
00:54:17,174 --> 00:54:22,054
My cousin Thomas and Virginia must be
at the movies, so they won't be home yet.

630
00:54:22,179 --> 00:54:25,516
- This is the kitchen.
- Yes, I know.

631
00:54:25,641 --> 00:54:27,893
Come on in the dining room.

632
00:54:33,525 --> 00:54:35,569
Sit down.

633
00:54:38,029 --> 00:54:40,407
You want somethin' to eat?
We got chicken.

634
00:54:40,532 --> 00:54:42,993
No, thank you.
I don't think I should stay long.

635
00:54:43,118 --> 00:54:46,204
Oh, sure.
Well, just take off your coat a minute.

636
00:55:00,553 --> 00:55:04,557
I was tellin' you my brother Nicky got
married last Sunday. It was a nice affair.

637
00:55:04,683 --> 00:55:08,519
They had a statue of a woman and there
was whisky spoutin' out of her mouth.

638
00:55:08,644 --> 00:55:13,150
I never saw anything so grand
in all my life. And what a meal!

639
00:55:13,275 --> 00:55:17,112
I'm a butcher, so I know
a pretty good hunk of meat when I see it.

640
00:55:17,237 --> 00:55:20,741
This was choice fillet right off
the top of the chuck. $1.80 a pound.

641
00:55:21,282 --> 00:55:24,203
If you want a cheaper cut of meat,
why, get rib steak.

642
00:55:24,328 --> 00:55:28,332
It's got a lot of waste on it, but it comes
to a buck and a quarter a pound,

643
00:55:28,458 --> 00:55:30,502
if it's trimmed.

644
00:55:31,502 --> 00:55:35,589
Listen, Clara... Make yourself comfortable.
You look all tense.

645
00:55:36,466 --> 00:55:38,510
Oh, I'm fine.

646
00:55:40,303 --> 00:55:43,306
You want me to take you home,
I'll take you home.

647
00:55:44,766 --> 00:55:47,227
Maybe it would be a good idea.

648
00:56:00,533 --> 00:56:03,411
- No, Marty.
- I like you. I been tellin' you all night I do.

649
00:56:03,536 --> 00:56:05,162
- Marty...
- All I want is a kiss.

650
00:56:05,288 --> 00:56:06,831
- Please. Please.
- No, Marty.

651
00:56:06,956 --> 00:56:10,085
All right. All right. I'll take you home!

652
00:56:10,210 --> 00:56:11,920
All I wanted was a lousy kiss.

653
00:56:12,045 --> 00:56:16,592
Think I'd try somethin' serious with
my mother comin' home any minute?

654
00:56:19,260 --> 00:56:21,930
I just didn't feel like it, that's all.

655
00:56:46,080 --> 00:56:48,124
Well...

656
00:56:50,168 --> 00:56:52,630
I'm old enough to know better.

657
00:56:55,673 --> 00:56:59,427
Come New Year's Eve,
everybody starts arrangin' parties.

658
00:57:01,471 --> 00:57:03,933
I'm the guy they gotta dig up a date for.

659
00:57:09,438 --> 00:57:12,358
I'll just get a pack of cigarettes and take...

660
00:57:20,575 --> 00:57:22,827
I'd like to see you again...

661
00:57:24,037 --> 00:57:26,081
very much.

662
00:57:28,208 --> 00:57:32,797
The reason I didn't let you kiss me
was because I just didn't know how to...

663
00:57:32,922 --> 00:57:35,382
handle the situation.

664
00:57:38,218 --> 00:57:40,888
You're the kindest man I ever met.

665
00:57:44,600 --> 00:57:48,980
The reason I tell you this is
because I want to see you again...

666
00:57:49,105 --> 00:57:51,149
very much.

667
00:57:53,068 --> 00:57:59,074
I know when you take me home I'm going
to lie on my bed and think about you.

668
00:58:02,744 --> 00:58:05,206
I want very much to see you again.

669
00:58:17,969 --> 00:58:20,596
What are you doin' tomorrow night?

670
00:58:23,390 --> 00:58:25,434
Nothing.

671
00:58:26,561 --> 00:58:29,022
I'll call you up tomorrow.

672
00:58:31,024 --> 00:58:33,568
Maybe we'll go see a movie.

673
00:58:33,693 --> 00:58:36,155
I'd like that very much.

674
00:58:40,450 --> 00:58:43,538
The reason I can't be
more definite now is...

675
00:58:45,455 --> 00:58:49,253
because my Aunt Catherine's
probably comin' over tomorrow.

676
00:58:49,377 --> 00:58:51,421
I may have to help out.

677
00:58:53,047 --> 00:58:55,508
I'll wait for your call.

678
00:59:06,269 --> 00:59:08,730
I better take you home now.

679
00:59:09,856 --> 00:59:13,235
It's gettin' late and the buses
only run about one an hour.

680
00:59:13,360 --> 00:59:15,696
All right.

681
00:59:15,821 --> 00:59:18,032
I'll just get a pack of cigarettes.

682
00:59:52,026 --> 00:59:54,904
What are you doin' New Year's Eve?

683
00:59:56,530 --> 00:59:58,574
Nothing.

684
01:00:17,720 --> 01:00:20,514
Hello! Hello! Marty?

685
01:00:24,059 --> 01:00:29,023
- Hello, Marty. When you come home?
- We just got here ten minutes ago, Ma.

686
01:00:29,148 --> 01:00:33,403
Ma, I want you to meet Miss Clara Snyder.
She's a graduate of New York University.

687
01:00:33,528 --> 01:00:36,365
She teaches chemistry
in Benjamin Franklin High School.

688
01:00:36,490 --> 01:00:38,701
Sit down. Sit down.

689
01:00:38,825 --> 01:00:41,536
You want some chicken?
We got chicken in the icebox.

690
01:00:41,661 --> 01:00:45,206
No, thank you, Mrs Piletti.
We were just going. Thank you anyway.

691
01:00:45,331 --> 01:00:49,878
Well, sit down just a minute. I just
come in the house. I take off my coat.

692
01:00:51,338 --> 01:00:57,553
- Did Thomas give you a ride?
- Sure. Is a sad business.

693
01:00:57,678 --> 01:01:01,057
My sister Caterina,
she no get along with her daughter-in-law,

694
01:01:01,182 --> 01:01:03,435
so she gonna come live with us.

695
01:01:03,560 --> 01:01:07,689
- Oh, she's comin', huh, Ma?
- Sure. Sit down. Sit down.

696
01:01:07,814 --> 01:01:11,484
- Marty, tell her sit down.
- Might as well sit down a minute, Clara.

697
01:01:11,609 --> 01:01:15,905
- You offer young lady some fruit?
- I offered her, but she don't want nothin'.

698
01:01:16,030 --> 01:01:18,074
No, thank you, really, Mrs Piletti.

699
01:01:18,199 --> 01:01:21,912
Is a very sad business, I tell you.

700
01:01:22,037 --> 01:01:26,958
A woman, 56 years old,
all her life she had her own house.

701
01:01:27,083 --> 01:01:32,381
Now she's just an old woman
sleeping on her daughter-in-law couch.

702
01:01:32,799 --> 01:01:35,593
It's a curse to be a mother, I tell you.

703
01:01:35,718 --> 01:01:40,598
Your children grow up
and then what is left for you to do?

704
01:01:40,723 --> 01:01:43,852
What is a mother's life but her children?

705
01:01:44,228 --> 01:01:49,400
Is a very sad thing when your son
has no place for you in his house.

706
01:01:49,526 --> 01:01:53,153
Well, couldn't she find
some kind of hobby to fill out her time?

707
01:01:53,278 --> 01:01:57,616
Hobby. Hobby. What can she do?
She cook and she clean.

708
01:01:57,741 --> 01:02:02,454
But you gotta have a house to clean
and you gotta have children to cook for.

709
01:02:04,123 --> 01:02:09,044
These are the terrible years for a mother.
The terrible years.

710
01:02:09,503 --> 01:02:12,842
You mustn't feel too harshly
against her daughter-in-law.

711
01:02:12,966 --> 01:02:17,553
She probably also wants to have a house
to clean and children to cook for.

712
01:02:17,928 --> 01:02:24,686
You don't think my sister Caterina
should live in her daughter-in-law house?

713
01:02:24,811 --> 01:02:31,485
Well, I don't know them, but, as a rule, a
mother-in-law shouldn't live with a couple.

714
01:02:31,610 --> 01:02:35,072
Where you think
a mother-in-law should go?

715
01:02:35,197 --> 01:02:40,411
I don't think a mother should depend so
much upon her children for her rewards.

716
01:02:40,536 --> 01:02:46,460
Well, that's what they teach you
in... New York University.

717
01:02:46,584 --> 01:02:49,754
In real life it no work out like this.

718
01:02:49,879 --> 01:02:52,131
You wait till you are a mother.

719
01:02:52,256 --> 01:02:56,887
It's silly of me to argue about it.
I... I don't know the people involved.

720
01:02:58,054 --> 01:03:02,726
Ma, I better take her home because
the buses only run about one an hour.

721
01:03:02,851 --> 01:03:03,852
Sure.

722
01:03:03,977 --> 01:03:07,272
Good night. I'm glad to have met you.
I hope I see you again.

723
01:03:07,397 --> 01:03:10,192
OK, Ma. I'll be back
in about an hour, an hour and a half.

724
01:03:10,317 --> 01:03:13,863
- Sure.
- Good night, Mrs Piletti.

725
01:03:13,988 --> 01:03:16,031
Good night.

726
01:03:23,916 --> 01:03:25,876
Hey!

727
01:03:26,209 --> 01:03:27,794
Hey!

728
01:03:28,086 --> 01:03:29,921
Hey, Marty! Hey!

729
01:03:30,046 --> 01:03:32,090
Hey, Ange!

730
01:03:35,971 --> 01:03:39,265
Marty, where you been?
I been lookin' all over for ya.

731
01:03:39,390 --> 01:03:42,018
I looked all over for you,
but I couldn't find you.

732
01:03:42,143 --> 01:03:44,187
Well, I was lookin' all over for you.

733
01:03:44,312 --> 01:03:46,439
We thought we were gonna go for a walk

734
01:03:46,564 --> 01:03:49,985
and then we thought we were gonna
come back, but we got to talkin'.

735
01:03:50,109 --> 01:03:52,988
I want you to meet Clara.
Clara, my best friend Angie.

736
01:03:53,112 --> 01:03:55,532
- I told you about him.
- Yes. How do you do?

737
01:03:55,657 --> 01:03:57,283
Hello.

738
01:03:58,201 --> 01:04:03,081
- What we gonna do now?
- I'm taking Clara home. It's close to one.

739
01:04:03,206 --> 01:04:06,876
- You want me to ride down with ya?
- What for?

740
01:04:07,002 --> 01:04:10,673
- It's early.
- It must be one o'clock.

741
01:04:10,798 --> 01:04:13,717
It's Saturday night!
There's still plenty of action around!

742
01:04:15,219 --> 01:04:18,263
Listen, by the time I get Clara home
it's gonna be 1.30.

743
01:04:18,388 --> 01:04:23,019
By the time I get home it'll be two. I gotta
get up for ten o'clock mass tomorrow.

744
01:04:24,897 --> 01:04:29,525
- OK. I'll see ya.
- Hey, well, where you goin'? Hey, Ange.

745
01:04:29,650 --> 01:04:32,361
Hey, I'll see ya tomorrow after mass, huh?

746
01:05:01,184 --> 01:05:03,228
You got an elevator in this house?

747
01:05:03,353 --> 01:05:05,397
We only live one flight up.

748
01:05:06,314 --> 01:05:08,775
OK. So I'll see you tomorrow.

749
01:05:09,401 --> 01:05:11,027
OK.

750
01:05:11,152 --> 01:05:15,616
Uh, I'll give you a call about 11, 11.30,
as soon as I get out of mass.

751
01:05:15,741 --> 01:05:21,831
Well, better make it around 2.30, because
I won't be home from my aunt's till then.

752
01:05:21,955 --> 01:05:24,124
Oh, OK.

753
01:05:34,052 --> 01:05:36,387
OK. So... I'll see you tomorrow night.

754
01:05:37,681 --> 01:05:39,307
OK.

755
01:05:40,559 --> 01:05:43,561
- Good night.
- Good night.

756
01:07:06,567 --> 01:07:08,609
Taxi! Hey, taxi!

757
01:07:09,193 --> 01:07:12,488
Taxi! Hey, taxi!

758
01:07:14,532 --> 01:07:16,367
Hey!

759
01:08:02,500 --> 01:08:05,252
Hey, Ma. You know what
I think I'm gonna do?

760
01:08:05,377 --> 01:08:07,921
I think I'm gonna buy Patsy's shop.

761
01:08:21,769 --> 01:08:24,356
You hear what I said, Ma?

762
01:08:24,481 --> 01:08:28,193
This is how I figure. We got
33-odd hundred dollars in the bank,

763
01:08:28,318 --> 01:08:31,739
so I'm gonna have to take it out
to buy the shop. So what do you think?

764
01:08:31,864 --> 01:08:33,281
I don't know.

765
01:08:33,406 --> 01:08:36,369
I'm a good butcher.
I think I'll make out pretty good.

766
01:08:36,494 --> 01:08:39,580
I wanna ask Thomas about this,
but I got my own ideas.

767
01:08:39,705 --> 01:08:41,582
Come on, Marty. It's nine o'clock.

768
01:08:41,707 --> 01:08:46,128
Listen, Ma, you mind comin' home alone
from church because I wanna find Angie?

769
01:08:46,253 --> 01:08:48,839
- I think he's sore at me for somethin'.
- OK.

770
01:08:48,964 --> 01:08:52,968
Ma, what I wanna ask you is, is Thomas
bringing Aunt Catherine here or what,

771
01:08:53,095 --> 01:08:55,264
because I wanna see him?

772
01:08:55,389 --> 01:08:59,309
I think Thomas is gonna bring Aunt
Caterina over here, but I don't know.

773
01:08:59,434 --> 01:09:02,563
Now, please go outside
because I gotta put on my clothes.

774
01:09:02,688 --> 01:09:05,774
All right. So what are you
gettin' so sore about?

775
01:09:12,198 --> 01:09:14,783
Marty? Please excuse what I say.

776
01:09:14,908 --> 01:09:16,952
OK, Ma.

777
01:09:21,290 --> 01:09:26,379
- Don't you think I feel lousy about it, too?
- I don't wanna talk any more about it.

778
01:09:27,088 --> 01:09:30,092
I don't think I got an hour's sleep
the whole night.

779
01:09:30,217 --> 01:09:33,303
Last night was the first time
I ever heard my mother cry.

780
01:09:33,428 --> 01:09:36,306
- Tommy, I...
- I don't wanna talk about it.

781
01:09:36,432 --> 01:09:41,603
I know what you're gonna say. A man's
gotta stop bein' his mother's baby.

782
01:09:41,728 --> 01:09:44,356
She's my mother.
I have some feelin' about her.

783
01:09:44,481 --> 01:09:48,194
- Why am I always made to be the louse?
- I don't wanna talk about it!

784
01:09:48,319 --> 01:09:52,615
Look, Tommy... Tommy, I love you
and I know you feel lousy right now,

785
01:09:52,740 --> 01:09:56,327
but we'll never be happy unless we have
a chance to work out our own lives.

786
01:09:56,453 --> 01:10:01,792
We can't keep talkin' in whispers the rest
of our lives. We gotta have some privacy.

787
01:10:06,171 --> 01:10:08,966
Ma! Can't you wait five minutes?
I'll drive you over.

788
01:10:09,091 --> 01:10:11,385
- I just gotta put on a shirt.
- Go to mass.

789
01:10:11,510 --> 01:10:14,305
I got time to go to mass.
I'll go to 11 o'clock mass.

790
01:10:14,430 --> 01:10:16,474
Let me drive you over, will you, Ma?

791
01:10:16,599 --> 01:10:18,643
Thomas, leave me alone.

792
01:10:25,774 --> 01:10:29,403
All right, get dressed because
we're gonna drive my mother over.

793
01:10:29,528 --> 01:10:32,156
Why couldn't you get along with her,
make an effort?

794
01:10:32,282 --> 01:10:35,119
She's hard to get along with.
All I asked you was to try!

795
01:10:35,244 --> 01:10:37,829
- Tommy...
- I don't wanna hear any more about it!

796
01:11:13,408 --> 01:11:15,243
Hello, Aunt Theresa.

797
01:11:15,368 --> 01:11:17,204
Hello, Tommy. How you feel?

798
01:11:17,329 --> 01:11:21,291
Ah, my mother... drives me crazy. I had
to beg her to let me drive her over here.

799
01:11:21,417 --> 01:11:23,961
- Oh.
- She's always gotta be the big martyr.

800
01:11:24,087 --> 01:11:26,339
Please, go to mass, huh?

801
01:11:26,464 --> 01:11:30,760
This one, he wake up this morning
with salt in his nose. Do this! Do that!

802
01:11:30,885 --> 01:11:33,888
Please leave me alone, huh?

803
01:11:34,848 --> 01:11:36,349
- Hello, Thomas.
- Hiya.

804
01:11:36,474 --> 01:11:39,394
Hello, Aunt Catherine.
You gonna go to mass with us?

805
01:11:39,519 --> 01:11:41,563
- I was to mass two hours ago.
- Oh, good.

806
01:11:41,689 --> 01:11:44,482
Make yourself at home.
The refrigerator's loaded.

807
01:11:44,607 --> 01:11:46,985
You go upstairs, take any room
you want, OK?

808
01:11:47,110 --> 01:11:49,446
Thomas!

809
01:11:49,571 --> 01:11:52,407
- You want a cup of coffee?
- Ah.

810
01:11:53,366 --> 01:11:56,078
Oh, hi, Virginia.
Oh, you brought him over, huh?

811
01:11:56,203 --> 01:11:58,580
Let me hold him for a minute.

812
01:11:58,706 --> 01:12:04,044
Hey, Petey boy. Yeah.
You're sure gettin' fat. You know that?

813
01:12:04,169 --> 01:12:07,298
Yeah. You're bigger
than a leg o' lamb now.

814
01:12:07,423 --> 01:12:10,385
So, Tom, like I was tellin' you
when you was over here,

815
01:12:10,510 --> 01:12:14,806
my boss wants to sell his shop, because
he wants to move out to California.

816
01:12:14,931 --> 01:12:18,060
- What are you so sore about?
- Shut up. Will you do me a favour?

817
01:12:18,185 --> 01:12:21,855
So, Tommy, he does about
$12-1300 gross. The rent's $102.

818
01:12:21,980 --> 01:12:25,150
The problem is the supermarkets.
That's what I wanna ask you.

819
01:12:25,275 --> 01:12:27,528
If I get together with other merchants...

820
01:12:27,653 --> 01:12:31,616
What about the time she wanted
to make dinner, but you wouldn't let her?

821
01:12:31,741 --> 01:12:35,536
- Once a month she can't use the kitchen.
- She could use it any time.

822
01:12:35,661 --> 01:12:38,623
- You had to be the boss.
- She wouldn't use my pots and pans.

823
01:12:38,747 --> 01:12:42,419
- Pots and pans, my foot!
- You want me to buy new pots and pans?

824
01:12:42,544 --> 01:12:45,755
Tommy... Tommy...
Look, just give me a coupla minutes.

825
01:12:45,880 --> 01:12:49,884
I told Mr Otari I'd let him know tomorrow.
You and Virginia can fight any time.

826
01:12:50,009 --> 01:12:53,388
Listen, I wanna know
about individualised mark-ups.

827
01:12:53,513 --> 01:12:57,058
Say I'm the butcher and Aldo Capelli
is the dairyman and the grocer,

828
01:12:57,184 --> 01:12:59,937
but he works on a...

829
01:13:00,062 --> 01:13:05,317
- Do you know what you're talkin' about?
- No, I don't. That's why I'm askin' you!

830
01:13:05,442 --> 01:13:07,277
Why d'you wanna buy a shop?

831
01:13:07,402 --> 01:13:11,365
You got a good job, no wife,
no responsibilities. Boy, I wish I was you.

832
01:13:11,490 --> 01:13:14,536
What do you wanna buy a shop for?
Take the baby, will ya?

833
01:13:14,660 --> 01:13:19,541
If he wants $5,000 down, you'll have
to carry a mortgage: $60, $70 a month.

834
01:13:19,666 --> 01:13:23,795
You're single with no responsibilities.
Stay that way. Take my advice.

835
01:13:23,921 --> 01:13:26,172
Why are you yellin'? He's askin' advice.

836
01:13:26,297 --> 01:13:29,092
Yeah, Tom, but Patsy's shop
is a specialised trade.

837
01:13:29,217 --> 01:13:33,973
- Supermarkets don't carry Italian meat.
- Who buys Italian? Think my wife does?

838
01:13:34,098 --> 01:13:38,560
She goes to the A&P, gets a lamb chop
wrapped in Cellophane, and that's dinner!

839
01:13:38,685 --> 01:13:41,647
- All right.
- I know the problem of the supermarkets,

840
01:13:41,773 --> 01:13:44,817
but I was talkin' to this girl last night...

841
01:13:44,942 --> 01:13:48,196
Look, Marty, will you see
my mother is nice and comfortable?

842
01:13:48,321 --> 01:13:51,700
- Oh, sure. But this girl...
- What girl? What does she know?

843
01:13:51,825 --> 01:13:54,286
Marty, take care of my mother, will ya?

844
01:14:08,217 --> 01:14:11,678
Hey, Ma, get ready,
cos I'll be down in a minute.

845
01:14:11,805 --> 01:14:13,848
- Hey, Caterina.
- Huh?

846
01:14:14,640 --> 01:14:20,063
Last night when I come home from
your house, Marty was here with a girl.

847
01:14:20,187 --> 01:14:22,274
- Who?
- Marty.

848
01:14:22,399 --> 01:14:23,816
Your son Marty?

849
01:14:23,941 --> 01:14:27,863
Well, which Marty you think
would be here in this house with a girl?

850
01:14:27,988 --> 01:14:31,115
- Were the lights on?
- Oh, sure.

851
01:14:31,240 --> 01:14:34,077
This girl is a college graduate.

852
01:14:34,202 --> 01:14:39,792
They're the worst. College girls
are one step from the street, I tell you.

853
01:14:39,917 --> 01:14:44,296
My son Joseph's wife,
you know, she type on a typewriter.

854
01:14:44,421 --> 01:14:46,841
One step from the street.

855
01:14:48,384 --> 01:14:51,638
This is the first time
Marty brang home a girl.

856
01:14:51,763 --> 01:14:56,643
She look like a nice girl. You know,
I think Marty has a feeling for this girl.

857
01:14:57,811 --> 01:15:00,813
You heard him sing?
Sing like that all morning.

858
01:15:01,690 --> 01:15:03,858
Well, that's all. You'll see.

859
01:15:04,526 --> 01:15:08,572
Today, tomorrow, in a week,
he's gonna say to you

860
01:15:08,697 --> 01:15:14,370
"Hey, Ma, I'm tired of running around.
It's no good to be a single man."

861
01:15:14,495 --> 01:15:18,624
Then he's gonna say to you "Hey, Ma.
Why we need this old house?"

862
01:15:18,749 --> 01:15:23,421
"Why don't we sell this old house
and move in a nicer part of town?"

863
01:15:23,546 --> 01:15:25,381
"Nice little apartment."

864
01:15:25,506 --> 01:15:27,593
I don't sell this house, I tell you that.

865
01:15:28,468 --> 01:15:32,555
This is my husband's house.
I had six children in this house.

866
01:15:32,681 --> 01:15:34,599
You'll see.

867
01:15:34,725 --> 01:15:39,396
In a couple of months you gonna be
an old lady sleeping on a couch

868
01:15:39,521 --> 01:15:42,942
- in your daughter-in-law's house.
- Ah, Caterina!

869
01:15:43,193 --> 01:15:45,235
Where you go, rain go!

870
01:15:45,360 --> 01:15:48,697
Someday you gonna smile,
we gonna have a big holiday.

871
01:15:48,822 --> 01:15:52,576
Hey, Ma. What do you say, Ma?
It's gettin' a little late, huh?

872
01:15:52,702 --> 01:15:54,537
Sure.

873
01:15:57,122 --> 01:16:02,795
Boy, this place is really comin' to pieces.
Ma, I think we oughta sell this place.

874
01:16:02,920 --> 01:16:05,381
The whole joint's goin' to pieces.

875
01:16:05,506 --> 01:16:10,679
Plumbing's rusty, everything. Now I'm
gonna have to replaster this whole place.

876
01:16:13,182 --> 01:16:15,476
You know what we oughta do, Ma?

877
01:16:15,601 --> 01:16:19,396
Get one of those new apartments
they're buildin' on Southern Boulevard.

